               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-160-person1359">
                  THOMAS 
                  HOBBS KING
               <interp inst="t18320705-160-person1359" type="surname" value="HOBBS KING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-160-person1359" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-160-person1359" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable N 248). On the 9th of June, I fell in with the two prisoners in Maiden-lane, about a quarter-past seven o'clock in the evening; one of them was in one field, and one in another - I saw Purvis crawl on his hands and knees, under the hedge, and then they both came out of the fields, and walked up the road - they then went into Cut-throat-lane, about three-quarters of a mile up the road; I there saw Purvis with his coat and waistcoat off, and he was putting on a striped shirt over his own shirt - I took them back, and in going back, Purvis said he had committed a robbery that would transport him, that he had robbed a poor laundress of eleven shirts, and two handkerchiefs - he told me to go and look under a bush, and I should find eleven shirts and a handkerchief in his flannel jacket; I went and found them - there was nothing found on Eather.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-160-person1360">
                  JAMES 
